First — Why Partitioning Alone Is Not Enough

Suppose table partitioned by:

sale_year = 2026

Good.

But January partition may still contain:
hundreds of millions rows
Now query:

SELECT *
FROM fact_sales
WHERE customer_id = 101;
Partitioning alone cannot help much.
Need better organization INSIDE partition.
That is clustering.
--
What is Clustering?

Theory
Clustering organizes data physically inside partitions (or tables) based on selected columns to improve query performance.
---

Simple Definition
Partitioning decides:
> “Which chunk?”
Clustering decides:

 “How data is arranged inside chunk?”
---
Example
Partitioning by Date
2026_January partition
Inside January partition:
Data clustered by:
customer_id⁹
Now rows of same customer stored closer together.

Queries become faster.

---

Important Insight ⭐

Partitioning reduces:

amount of data scanned
Clustering reduces:
work inside scanned data
Both work together.
---

Real Example — E-commerce
At Amazon
fact_sales
Partitioned by:
order_date
Clustered by:

customer_id

product_category
Why?
Most queries filter:
recent dates
customer activity
category sales
---

How Clustering Improves Performance
Without clustering:
customer rows scattered everywhere
Database scans many blocks.
---

With clustering:
similar customer rows stored together
Less scanning needed.
---
Common Clustering Columns ⭐
Column	Why
customer_id	frequent filtering
product_id	analytical queries
region	regional reporting
category	grouped aggregations
---

Difference Between Partitioning and Clustering ⭐⭐⭐

Feature	Partitioning	Clustering

Purpose	Split large table	Organize inside partitions
Granularity	Large chunks	Fine-grained ordering
Best For	Date filtering	Frequent query columns
Example	year/month	customer_id



